	abstract = {Background. Thought disorder has been proposed as an indicator of schizotypy, which is considered to be necessary but not suﬃcient for the development of schizophrenia. It is unclear whether thought disorder is an indicator of susceptibility (i.e. an endophenotype) for schizophrenia. The goal of the present study was to elucidate the role of thought disorder in relation to schizotypy by examining its presence in high-risk individuals during mid-childhood.
